When the LTA offered Miss Broady funding again the following year, it was turned down on principle.

The family continued its boycott until last year when Liam, now 20 and on the men’s circuit, decided to accept LTA funding again – a move that has angered his father to the point where they are no longer on speaking terms.

'It’s a very touchy subject,' Broady, who also has a sister and another brother, said.

'Dad says he was trying to protect us, but now Liam is older and has to pay for tennis himself. It’s a difficult family issue. I try to stay out of it.'

But she insists she will not follow her brother’s example. ‘I don’t want their money and now  I have the prize money from Wimbledon I don’t need it,’ she said. ‘I won’t be bought by them after everything that’s happened.

